description: From Middle English tyke, teke, from Old English ticia (“parasitic animal, tick”), from Proto-Germanic *tīkkô, suffixed variant of Proto-Germanic *tīgô, compare Dutch teek, German Zecke.

entries.meaning: A tiny woodland arachnid of the suborder Ixodida.

description: From Middle English tek (“light touch, tap”).

entries.meaning: A relatively quiet but sharp sound generally made repeatedly by moving machinery.
examples: The steady tick of the clock provided a comforting background for the conversation.

entries.meaning: A mark on any scale of measurement; a unit of measurement.
examples: At midday, the long bond is up a tick.

entries.meaning: (computing) A jiffy (unit of time defined by basic timer frequency).
(colloquial) A short period of time, particularly a second.
examples: I'll be back in a tick.

entries.meaning: (video games) A periodic increment of damage or healing caused by an ongoing status effect.
(Australia, New Zealand, Britain, Ireland) A mark (✓) made to indicate agreement, correctness or acknowledgement.
examples: Indicate that you are willing to receive marketing material by putting a tick in the box

entries.meaning: (birdwatching) A bird seen (or heard) by a birdwatcher, for the first time that day, year, trip, etc., and thus added to a list of observed birds.
(ornithology) The whinchat.

verbs.description: tick (third-person singular simple present ticks, present participle ticking, simple past and past participle ticked)

entries.meaning: To make a clicking noise similar to the movement of the hands in an analog clock.
To make a tick or checkmark.
(informal, intransitive) To work or operate, especially mechanically.
examples: He took the computer apart to see how it ticked.
I wonder what makes her tick.

entries.meaning: To strike gently; to pat.
(birdwatching, transitive) To add (a bird) to a list of birds that have been seen (or heard).

description: From Middle English tike, probably from Middle Dutch, from Latin theca (“cover”).

entries.meaning: (uncountable) Ticking.
A sheet that wraps around a mattress; the cover of a mattress, containing the filling.
(UK, colloquial) Credit, trust.

verbs.description: tick (third-person singular simple present ticks, present participle ticking, simple past and past participle ticked)

entries.meaning: (intransitive) To go on trust, or credit.
(transitive) To give tick; to trust.

description: From Middle English tik-, tic-, tike-, tiken- (in compounds), an unassibilated form of Middle English tiche, tichen (“young goat”), from Old English tiċċen (“young goat; kid”), from Proto-West Germanic *tikkīn (“goatling”), diminutive of Proto-West Germanic *tigā (“goat”). Cognate with regional German Zicke (“nanny goat”), from Ziege (“goat; nanny goat”).

entries.meaning: (obsolete, place names) A goat.
examples: Tickhill, Tickham, Ticknock, Tickenhall Drive, Tickenhill Manor, Tickenhurst
